comments.body: Yes! Except the leaves are not part of the inflorescence, they are below (proximal) to the inflorescence, even though they sometimes resemble the bracts, especially where they transition on the stem. The corolla is composed of the beak (two fused petals) and the lower lip (three modified petals), which are distal to the entirely fused proximal corolla tube. The calyces have four distal lobes of wildly different sorts and are fused proximally.  These are subtended and often covered by the floral bracts, which very often are contrastingly and brightly colored.
I am starting to see it, I realize in Castilleja  there are, besides corolla and calyx  also bracts and  even leaves seemingly part of the flower, here yellowish.

ehhh am i correct in understanding: the calyx (normally the sepals) have lobes, and the corolla  normally the petals) have lips. Yes? the beak would be the... aha i am seeing something: is the beak white and is it the beak of the corolla,  where here in these pictures the stigma is popping out, the seed growing taller. ?
